*I can relate to this man's story so much. Now before you laugh at me, read my story.*

I was 8 years old and I exited out of my room on the second floor.

I wanted to eat some Frosted Flakes and it was 8 am in the morning. I saw a squirrel at the top of the stairs.

I said "hello cute squirrel. wanna be my friend?"

The squirrel jumped on my face and started attacking me. I was like "ahhhh" and I fell tumbling down the stairs. The squirrel escaped through an opening in the window. 

I was so injured. I couldn't walk. I couldn't sit. So I crawled to the kitchen. I grabbed a bowl, spoon, and frosted flakes. I crawled to the fridge but there was no milk. NO MILK! 

I was so betrayed. So defeated. I cried.

Title: The Revenant | Official Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: If anybody is in two minds as to whether to go and see this film: do (especially while it's in cinemas). The way this story is told just brutally highlights the futility of existence, and one man's genuinely inhuman struggle despite it. It's a tour de force of human spirit in the face of absolute, unequivocal hopelessness. It leaves you in a state of existential crisis. It fills you with the fear of God, quivering from the almighty savagery of nature. The performance from DiCaprio alone is unbelievable, and Hardy, despite having a smaller role, might be even better. The incomparable cinematography and mind-breaking audio design is worth the $15 to see in the cinema. Best film of 2015, no doubt.

Title: The Revenant | Official Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
My rating 4/5 
In terms of immersion and beauty this film is quite revolutionary. I felt like I was actually in that period and environment in a way that even previous films hadnt made me feel, Refn's "Valhalla Rising" or Herzog's "Aguirre Wrath of God" (check them both out if you like this). The cinematography and score are excellent. The performances great across the board, Leo's is a terrific physical performance, Hardy is superb as the villain. Will Poulter, Forrest Goodluck and Gleeson in the supporting roles are all excellent. However I find the personal human journey (revenge) in the film good but nothing special. It wasnt what stuck with me afterwards, instead it was the enormity of sheer force, brutality and beauty of the landscape. And of Man vs Nature. It is a visceral and cold movie. I never felt emotional and some of the dream/flashback sequences did work, others didnt. Perhaps the whole point was that Revenge is cold and empty, im not sure. Overall it is a brilliant film and worth seeing, it wont be half as good at home, so please see it at the cinema!

This movie, is simply a remake of "Man in The Wilderness" (1971) and frankly "Man in The Wilderness" was WAY better...it actually had a story-line! If the film maker had mentioned that this was a remake, I'd be more respectful, but this is like a songwriter, writing a hit song and being sued for copying all of the same chord progressions and melody lines, from someone else's song.  I would be embarrassed if I were this film maker.

Title: The Revenant | Official Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Having now seen the film my opinion is this. . . it's a very well-made film but it's overlong at 2 & a half hours and, although the cinematography is beautiful , there are far too many upward shots of trees (the first time, you think wow, but after 20 similar shots it loses impact).
It's a kind of Braveheart meets Deliverance - indeed the visions of Leo's former wife are straight out of Braveheart - especially the final scene.
Tom Hardy is excellent - his character really coming across. So, too, is Will Poulter. But, for me, although Leo has to endure some harrowing scenes, his emotions don't change at all. He only has about half a dozen lines but keeps his performance on the same level throughout the entire film. I wanted him to be so good in this but he gives nothing away - not anger, not hurt, nothing. I felt nothing for him.
I'm sure it will win loads of Oscars, but it left me absolutely cold & not a film I would bother watching again.  But, look, that's me. you'll probably love it !

Title: The Revenant | Official Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: I'm so excited for this film year... Since I live in the Netherlands, some of the great films already made this year aren't released here yet, such as Sicario, but when I see all the trailers, I think 2015 will go down as one of the greatest film years of this century so far. Take a look at the films released this year... Kingsman: The Secret Service, It Follows, McFarland USA, Avengers: Age of Ultron, Mad Max: Fury Road, Spy, Jurassic World, Inside Out, Ant-Man, Trainwreck, Southpaw, Straight Outta Compton, Sicario, The Martian, The Walk, Bridge of Spies, Crimson Peak... I've not seen all these films yet, but I am soooo excited to check them all out when they are released in cinemas in the Netherlands. And based on the many trailers for the releases that will come this year, I am very much looking forward to Spectre (of course), Trumbo, By the Sea, Carol, Legend, Secret in Their Eyes, The Good Dinosaur, The Danish Girl, The Big Short, In the Heart of the Sea, Star Wars: The Force Awakens, Concussion, The Hateful Eight, Joy and of course this film, The Revenant. And in early 2016, Silence by Martin Scorsese and Hail Caesar! by the Coen brothers are getting released too... I feel like a kid in a candy store this year.

Title: The Revenant | Official Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Reading these comments, it's apparent that most people on YouTube have no idea how Oscars work. They're not given to the person with the best filmography. They're not given to the person who's been consistently good for many years. They're given to the actor who gave the single best performance that year. Leo has given a lot of great performances in a lot of great movies, but none of that means anything for the 2015 Oscars. The only thing that matters is the single performance he gives in 2015 (so the one in this movie). And if someone with fewer great performances gives one performance this year that's better than the one Leo gives, then that other person should and will win the Oscar.

None of you have seen Leo's performance in this movie. None of you have seen the other great performances that will come out later this year. And yet hundreds of you are saying that Leo deserves the Oscar. And to top it all off, many of you have the gaul to say that the academy is the one who's biased. That's just a depressing amount of stupidity.

Comment: Dicaprio should never have won an Oscar. Nominated for the Aviator in 2004; Clint Eastwood's performance in Million Dollar Baby and Jamie Foxx's for Ray were far superior. Nominated for Blood Diamond in 2006 which is an incredible film - Forest Whitaker as Idi Amin in Last King of Scotland was superior. Dicaprio was great in Wolf of Wall Street, but McConaughey and Ejiofor were better that year. Tommy Lee Jones was better in the Fugitive in 1993 as well. Really, his best chance at winning was 2013, but he was going up against simply better actors. Anyway, an Oscar win isn't important anyway. As long as he is being appreciated for his fantastic work by us, the audience, then an Oscar isn't necessary to validate that. So please stop going on about how Leo hasn't won an Oscar, because he is a great actor nonetheless.

And ladies and gentlemen I think we might be in store for one of the most important films of the decade.¬†

Really interested to see if the lead oscar race will come down between DiCaprio (For this film) and his co-star Tom Hardy (who could easily snag a supporting nomination here as well as lead actor nom for the upcoming "Legend" yet another film that looks incredible based off initial trailers)
